00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:31.720
So that $15 million per year problem.

00:03:31.720 --> 00:03:36.880
So you guys might recognize this gentleman's face, Bill Gates.

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:44.520
He was once quoted as saying, you take away our top 20 employees and overnight, we, Microsoft,

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:47.119
become a mediocre company.

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:49.520
Let's dissect what he's saying there.

00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:50.520
Take away.

00:03:50.520 --> 00:03:56.039
He's talking about a concept called employee attrition, employee turnover.

00:03:56.039 --> 00:03:57.360
Top 20.

00:03:57.360 --> 00:03:59.119
He's talking about high performers.

00:03:59.119 --> 00:04:06.600
This is the top 20 people in his company, and often what we find is the 80-20 rule applies.

00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:11.559
Top 20% of employees in a company tend to generate about 80% of the results.

00:04:11.559 --> 00:04:17.920
So you really want to do what you can to preserve and keep and retain those high performers.

00:04:17.920 --> 00:04:23.679
Otherwise, your company is going to become a mediocre company.

00:04:23.679 --> 00:04:25.440
So let's dive into this a little bit further.

00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:27.279
I want to talk about this curve.

00:04:27.279 --> 00:04:30.679
It's called the economic value of an employee over time.

00:04:30.679 --> 00:04:32.480
It looks a little bit like this.

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:35.119
So we'll see that there's four different boxes up here.

00:04:35.119 --> 00:04:37.239
The first box is the curve.

00:04:37.239 --> 00:04:43.119
So when an employee just starts at a company, they represent that green dot there right

00:04:43.119 --> 00:04:44.399
at the beginning.

00:04:44.399 --> 00:04:50.079
So time has not elapsed, and actually what is happening is that company is investing

00:04:50.079 --> 00:04:53.980
and actually losing money having you as part of that company.

00:04:53.980 --> 00:04:56.000
And that's an investment that they're making in you.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.640
So they have to provide you training, mentorship, they have to integrate you, and it takes a

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:05.760
while to do this before you can become a productive member of that company.

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:11.079
Then eventually you make it to the second box, and this is what's called the break-even

00:05:11.079 --> 00:05:12.079
point.

00:05:12.079 --> 00:05:17.640
So as you gradually get to that point where you begin to start generating returns for

00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:18.640
that company.

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:19.640
And they call that the return zone.

00:05:19.640 --> 00:05:23.019
So you've got the investment zone, you've got the return zone.

00:05:23.019 --> 00:05:29.040
And that process can take as little as three weeks for jobs that aren't overly difficult

00:05:29.040 --> 00:05:31.119
or for highly technical jobs.

00:05:31.119 --> 00:05:34.119
It can take upwards of a year or longer.

00:05:34.119 --> 00:05:38.559
So that's the type of investment that that company is making in you.

00:05:38.559 --> 00:05:41.760
So what happens when a person decides to quit?

00:05:41.760 --> 00:05:44.559
That's what this third box represents.

00:05:44.559 --> 00:05:49.079
So that employee has become a productive member of the company.

00:05:49.079 --> 00:05:53.720
They're generating returns, doing really good work, and then all of a sudden they decide

00:05:53.720 --> 00:05:54.720
to quit.

00:05:54.720 --> 00:05:57.279
And that could be because they hate their boss.

00:05:57.279 --> 00:06:01.519
That could be because their work-life balance is all out of whack.

00:06:01.519 --> 00:06:05.760
Or they may just not be like the work that they're doing.

00:06:05.760 --> 00:06:10.760
And what ends up happening is when that person quits, that line immediately drops down to

00:06:10.760 --> 00:06:15.320
zero, and then it extends for a period of time, and eventually that company decides

00:06:15.320 --> 00:06:19.320
to replace that person, typically.

00:06:19.320 --> 00:06:21.239
And then that cycle repeats itself.

00:06:21.239 --> 00:06:26.119
So they're reinvesting in the new person, getting them up to speed, and it takes a while

00:06:26.119 --> 00:06:28.220
before they get to the return zone.

00:06:28.220 --> 00:06:34.760
So as you can see in box number four, we've got lost time and lost productivity.

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:39.920
This is what you want to avoid, especially for high performers.

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:45.359
So there's two different types of attrition, and we're going to focus on trying to prevent

00:06:45.359 --> 00:06:47.799
your high-performing employees from leaving.

00:06:47.799 --> 00:06:52.160
So not all employees are created equally.

00:06:52.160 --> 00:06:55.760
Some employees just never quite get there.

00:06:55.820 --> 00:06:59.540
And that's what this first box here is what we call necessary attrition.

00:06:59.540 --> 00:07:04.299
And this could be because that person just might not be a good fit for the culture of

00:07:04.299 --> 00:07:09.779
the company, may not mesh well, it might be a poor job fit.

00:07:09.779 --> 00:07:15.779
Whatever reason, they just don't quite cut it, and it's okay to lose these people.

00:07:15.779 --> 00:07:20.540
But what you really want to prevent is the right-hand box, which is bad attrition.

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:24.820
And this is when you have high performers that have generated returns, you don't want

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:28.480
to see them leave the organization.

00:07:28.480 --> 00:07:34.640
So you can actually assign a dollar figure to this particular problem, and it's actually

00:07:34.640 --> 00:07:36.200
a very simple calculation.

00:07:36.200 --> 00:07:37.880
In fact, this is some R code.

00:07:37.880 --> 00:07:44.000
I know it might be a little bit difficult to read, but what this is is a function that

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:45.000
I created.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:50.399
It's called calculate attrition cost, and it takes a few different parameters, and then

00:07:50.399 --> 00:07:57.660
it performs just a vectorized calculation that incorporates direct costs, lost productivity,

00:07:57.660 --> 00:08:02.140
and some assumptions in there, and then also it subtracts out the salary and benefits,

00:08:02.140 --> 00:08:07.579
which is what the company actually benefits from losing an employee.

00:08:07.579 --> 00:08:13.540
So for a high-performing employee that is a productive member of that company, it can

00:08:13.540 --> 00:08:21.200
be upwards of $78,000 per employee that that company loses when you assign a cost to it.

00:08:21.200 --> 00:08:26.399
So the funny thing that happens is typically companies don't just lose one person, it ends

00:08:26.399 --> 00:08:29.640
up being more of a systemic issue.

00:08:29.640 --> 00:08:35.559
And so what happens when a company such as, say, Walmart or Target, you know, a competitor

00:08:35.559 --> 00:08:42.440
moves in and starts stealing your high performers, before you know it, you've got a couple hundred

00:08:42.440 --> 00:08:50.859
that you've lost, and if you lose 200 performers each year, that's a $15 million problem.

00:08:50.859 --> 00:08:52.299
Yikes.

00:08:52.299 --> 00:08:55.979
So we want to prevent these high performers from leaving the company.

00:08:55.979 --> 00:08:58.179
I think that's pretty obvious by now.

00:08:58.179 --> 00:09:01.940
So the way we can do that is through using data science.

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:06.500
And I'm going to show you the product first, just because I want to show you guys the end

00:09:06.500 --> 00:09:07.739
result.

00:09:07.739 --> 00:09:10.739
So we're going to do a quick, shiny web app demo.

00:09:10.739 --> 00:09:14.520
And again, this is something that's exclusive to the RStudio conference, I'm really excited

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:17.039
about this.

00:09:17.039 --> 00:09:22.520
This is what we're developing as part of the 300 series course, so there's a 100, a 200,

00:09:22.520 --> 00:09:26.799
and a 300, and those who take that course are going to be able to learn how to build

00:09:26.799 --> 00:09:27.799
this app.

00:09:27.799 --> 00:09:34.859
So I'm just going to click this run app button, and if all goes well, we get a shiny app.

00:09:34.859 --> 00:09:39.099
So what this app represents is the end product.

00:09:39.099 --> 00:09:45.940
You can imagine that you've got managers out there that are responsible for their employees.

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:51.219
They are responsible for retaining them, making sure that they develop them into productive

00:09:51.219 --> 00:09:53.500
people, making sure that they're happy.

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:56.140
And that's exactly what this app allows us to do.

00:09:56.140 --> 00:10:02.880
So I'm just going to scroll and kind of show you, each one of these numbers represents

00:10:02.880 --> 00:10:05.900
a specific employee.

00:10:05.900 --> 00:10:13.659
And this particular one, employee number 891, has a 47% prediction risk.

00:10:13.659 --> 00:10:18.859
So this is, this employee is actually predicted to leave, because that prediction risk is

00:10:18.859 --> 00:10:23.859
above the threshold for deciding whether or not that employee leaves.

00:10:23.859 --> 00:10:29.940
And this is actually H2O under the hood that's generating this predictive model, and the

00:10:29.940 --> 00:10:32.619
app is encapsulating it.

00:10:32.619 --> 00:10:34.619
So you can imagine, put yourself in that manager's shoes.

00:10:34.619 --> 00:10:41.419
They see that they've got an employee that's 47% likely to leave, and then what we have

00:10:41.419 --> 00:10:48.280
over here are the reasons, the features, of why that person is predicted to leave.

00:10:48.280 --> 00:10:53.979
So this actually comes from the Lime package, and this first feature here is stock option.

00:10:53.979 --> 00:10:57.840
So that person has stock option level 0.

00:10:57.840 --> 00:11:01.099
So this is something that the manager can actually affect, or change.

00:11:01.099 --> 00:11:03.219
It's what's called a lever.

00:11:03.219 --> 00:11:06.039
It's a feature that the manager can adjust.

00:11:06.039 --> 00:11:10.919
So maybe moving that employee from level 0 to level 1 and giving that employee stock

00:11:10.919 --> 00:11:15.580
options, that might be enough to help that employee to stay.

00:11:15.580 --> 00:11:20.960
The next one is the employee has over 28 years at the company.

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:27.840
The next one is that the number of jobs that that employee worked at is over 6.

00:11:27.859 --> 00:11:34.099
And then the next one is that that person has a training time last year of 2.

00:11:34.099 --> 00:11:37.260
So these two here are not levers that can be adjusted.

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:42.179
You can't really toggle the number of years that that employee works, or how many jobs

00:11:42.179 --> 00:11:47.539
that they've had previously, but that manager can then take a look at maybe training times,

00:11:47.539 --> 00:11:52.219
maybe to help get them engaged, give them a few more training sessions a year.

00:11:52.219 --> 00:11:54.179
So this is really cool.

00:11:54.179 --> 00:11:59.419
We're able to actually bottle up data science into this machine learning app, and even further

00:11:59.419 --> 00:12:07.320
than that, we can develop predictive recommendations that are able to be presented to the manager.

00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:12.320
So that way they don't have to kind of think of strategies to do, but that's already incorporated

00:12:12.320 --> 00:12:13.679
for them.

00:12:13.679 --> 00:12:18.119
So for example, this management recommendation strategy has a work environment strategy of

00:12:18.119 --> 00:12:19.900
promote job engagement.

00:12:19.900 --> 00:12:24.580
So that manager should then focus on activities that will promote job engagement.

00:12:24.580 --> 00:12:26.820
So this is what we're talking about.

00:12:26.820 --> 00:12:34.359
When we provide shiny web apps to non-technical people, business leaders that have a stake

00:12:34.359 --> 00:12:39.619
in the game where they can actually affect and make decisions that better improve the

00:12:39.619 --> 00:12:43.960
company, that can make a huge difference.

00:12:43.960 --> 00:12:46.260
So let's talk about that next.

00:12:46.260 --> 00:12:49.219
Let's go here.

00:12:49.219 --> 00:12:52.299
So this is what I call the better decision making effect.

00:12:52.299 --> 00:12:57.940
This is when you start to have, you provide the shiny web app to the decision makers in

00:12:57.940 --> 00:12:59.260
your company.

00:12:59.260 --> 00:13:03.020
You see that they're making, you've trained them on the app, how to use it, and you see

00:13:03.020 --> 00:13:05.219
them making positive decisions.

00:13:05.219 --> 00:13:10.099
What ends up happening is as you monitor the impact of the decision making improvements,

00:13:10.099 --> 00:13:15.559
you can start to see your percentage of attrition going down, down, and down.

00:13:15.559 --> 00:13:20.960
So it starts up here around 20%, ending in about a year at 9%.

00:13:20.960 --> 00:13:26.239
And then you can actually use that cost of attrition function to calculate how much you're

00:13:26.239 --> 00:13:28.599
saving the organization.

00:13:28.599 --> 00:13:32.119
And then how does that look when you show your boss at the end of the year, hey, I just

00:13:32.119 --> 00:13:35.640
saved you, our company, $4.3 million.

00:13:35.640 --> 00:13:38.140
I mean, that looks pretty good.

00:13:38.140 --> 00:13:43.320
And you'll probably get a, I don't know, maybe a promotion out of it.

00:13:43.400 --> 00:13:45.640
Anyways, the better decision making effect.

00:13:45.640 --> 00:13:50.679
That's what I want to get across here is that we can use shiny apps to actually influence

00:13:50.679 --> 00:13:53.880
the decisions within our own organizations.

00:13:53.880 --> 00:13:56.940
And that's how we generate business value.

00:13:56.940 --> 00:14:01.200
So what I want to talk about next now is the data science workflow.

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:03.559
So we talked a lot about the end product.

00:14:03.559 --> 00:14:05.760
Hopefully you like the app.

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:10.299
And now what I want to do is talk about the process to get to that app.

00:14:10.299 --> 00:14:14.340
So how do you go from business problem to business value?

00:14:14.340 --> 00:14:19.140
It requires a process that can be shown as a workflow.

00:14:19.140 --> 00:14:24.700
There's three stages, preparation, experimentation, and distribution.

00:14:24.700 --> 00:14:28.859
So in the preparation stage, you're acquiring data and you're reformatting and cleaning

00:14:28.859 --> 00:14:30.739
data.

00:14:30.739 --> 00:14:34.859
At that stage, then you move into the learning, which is the experimentation phase.

00:14:34.859 --> 00:14:38.599
You've got your data, you're coming up with hypotheses, you're meeting with stakeholders

00:14:38.599 --> 00:14:44.080
in the company that know that data inside and out to help you develop your strategies.

00:14:44.080 --> 00:14:47.559
And then you move into the transformation and visualization stage.

00:14:47.559 --> 00:14:50.020
And then you get to modeling and validation.

00:14:50.020 --> 00:14:52.840
And then, oh, you find, okay, we aren't getting a good model yet.

00:14:52.840 --> 00:14:57.719
I've got to go back and reevaluate our hypotheses.

00:14:57.719 --> 00:15:00.200
Or you may have to go back and acquire data.

00:15:00.200 --> 00:15:06.239
So you've got kind of this process that's iterative, and eventually you get a model

00:15:06.359 --> 00:15:11.919
that starts to show improvement, that gives you an idea that there could be a possibility

00:15:11.919 --> 00:15:14.039
of changing decisions.

00:15:14.039 --> 00:15:19.359
You then move into that final phase of distribution, you develop reports, you convince people in

00:15:19.359 --> 00:15:23.960
the company, executive leadership, that this is the right thing to do.

00:15:23.960 --> 00:15:29.340
And then you build an app and you deploy it and you start getting those business results.

00:15:29.340 --> 00:15:32.080
So that's how you generate business value.

00:15:32.080 --> 00:15:37.200
What I want to show you is the Tidyverse.

00:15:37.200 --> 00:15:39.020
It's a perfect fit.

00:15:39.020 --> 00:15:42.020
You can see we've got a bunch of packages that I've overlaid.

00:15:42.020 --> 00:15:45.039
You've got ReadR for reading in data.

00:15:45.039 --> 00:15:51.520
You've got Deplier, Tidier, StringR, Lubridate for time series, StringR for text, Forecats

00:15:51.520 --> 00:15:55.479
for categorical data to help you clean that data.

00:15:55.479 --> 00:15:58.080
You get into the experimentation stage.

00:15:58.080 --> 00:16:03.599
And once you're doing the visualization and the transformations, you're working with Deplier

00:16:03.599 --> 00:16:10.080
and ggplot2, H2O, once you get into the modeling and validation, and then you move into reporting,

00:16:10.080 --> 00:16:15.159
you've got R Markdown and then deployment, you've got Shiny.

00:16:15.159 --> 00:16:16.159
It just fits.

00:16:16.159 --> 00:16:18.580
And this is what I call the Arc toolchain.

00:16:18.580 --> 00:16:19.640
It's a fabulous toolchain.

00:16:19.640 --> 00:16:25.320
I've been teaching it for quite a while, and I'll tell you what, this gets results.

00:16:25.320 --> 00:16:32.039
So if we examine our workflow, Deplier, it's awesome for sizing the problem, identifying

00:16:32.039 --> 00:16:35.000
where we've got issues in our data.

